B06E-6464A831C9CA"><gtr:id>275D3321-FC75-45A4-B06E-6464A831C9CA</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Christina</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Koutra</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE011659%2F1"><gtr:id>905C142C-BE21-4484-8A87-7379EABF4AB6</gtr:id><gtr:title>More Than Simply Corporate Social Responsibility: Implications of CSR for Tourism Development and Poverty Alleviation in Less Developed Countries</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E011659/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Tourism was introduced in Elmina and Cape Coast (Ghana) for economic development, community uplift, and ultimately, poverty reduction. It was developed around three World Heritage sites, two castles and a fortress, which functioned as slave dungeons during 400 years of transatlantic slave trading. However, more than 15 years after its introduction tourism made no discernable difference to local realities due to inadequacy in building capacities at social, human, physical and financial levels by national and external state developmental institutions. By applying the metaphor of 'corporations' to such institutions doctoral fieldwork demonstrated that a lack of Corporate Social Responsibility, labelled hereafter [C (SR)], lies behind the failure. The research hypothesises that [C (SR)] should be a pre-requisite in employing tourism as a tool for poverty reduction. The focus will be on both the Ghanaian?s government responsibility and accountability towards its citizens and that of corporations contracted by donor agencies to operate tourism projects in the towns under study. The research through participatory research approaches will provide new insights into the complex relationships between development institutions, the tourism sector and local people. The findings will be useful for policymakers and planners seeking ways to achieve the Millennium Development Goals through tourism.
